<br>
  GM Tropheys can be made from any tradeskill other than alchemy.  All of them are trivial above 250 skill, with an estimated success rate of 33% at max skill.  All of them are Primary Secondary Range Ammo (though no stats work from the ammo slot) and are 10 str 10 int 10 wis 50 charisma.  The poisons trophey (Grandmaster Assassin's Vial) has 10 dex as well.  They all have a 5% skill modifier to the tradeskill that makes them, and all have a right click unlimited use summon of a 10 slot no rent lore  no drop 100% weight reduction bag, which can be turned into a gnome in the bazaar for a rentable version of the same.  <br>
<br>
  Tropheys are made by combining an Artisan's Seal with one or two items related to your tradeskill (Sculption Tools for Pottery, Sealed Poison Vial for Poisons, for example), with a 33% success rate at 250 skill.  The artisan's seal is made by combining one Mounted Blue Diamond, one Mounted Diamond, one Mounted Jacinth, and one Mounted Black Saphire, plus a block of clay (small I think) and a vial of Pure mana in a pottery wheel, then firing it with a high quality firing sheet.  Trivial for the first combine is somewhere under 110, the second is probably 15 skill.  Mounted gems are made by combining two enchanted bars of velium and the gem in question in a Jewelery Kit, trivial somewhere under 120.  Vials of pure mana require one poison vial and four rubies, and are made by enchanters.<br>
<br>
Costly to make, as you can imagine.<br>
<br>
  Gearlocks<br>
<br>
  Gearlocks, like all other skill modifying items, increase you skill for purposes of determining success or failure only.  In other words, a 200 skill Potter with a Pottery Gearlock (or GM Potter's Sculptor) would succeed as though he or she had 210 skill in Pottery.  Note that skill modifiers do not stack, only the highest modifier is taken, and that trivials are unaffected (so if you had 215 skill in pottery and a Gearlock, Opal Steins would still not be trivial to you, even though they go trivial at 220).  Also, this means that in the low 240s you max out your skill, since 252 is the highest possible modified skill level the game recognises.<br>
<br>
Highest Level<br>
<br>
Skills max out at 250, though gearlocks and other modifiers can max your effective skill at 252.<br>
<br>
  Multi-Mastering<br>
<br>
With the New Tanaan Crafting Mastery AA, which costs 3 points, you can grandmaster a second skill.  This AA can be gotten enough times to grandmaster all the skills, at a cost of 3 AA points per skill beyond the first.  Which skill you are allowed to GM is based on whichever skill you raise above 200 first.<br>
<br>
Gnome foraging<br>
<br>
Seduce/Bribe/Kidnap a ranger, or do all three.<br>
